{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a1d4b9e0-1d88-44e4-8b31-d10df46595e7","content":"The template is **functional but not fully publish-ready**. Here's what I found:\n\n**✅ Present (required)**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `tags`, `classifications` — all good.\n\n**⚠️ Missing (recommended before publishing)**\n\n| Field | Why it matters |\n|---|---|\n| `$schema` | Enables IDE validation. Use `\"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` |\n| `description` | Displayed in `dotnet new list` and on NuGet Gallery — without it the template looks incomplete |\n| `groupIdentity` | Required for clean version upgrades on NuGet (e.g. `\"MyCompany.WebApi.CSharp\"`) |\n| `preferNameDirectory` | Should be `true` for project templates so `dotnet new mywebapi -n Foo` creates a `Foo/` directory |\n\n**💡 Optional but worth considering**\n- A `postActions` entry for automatic `dotnet restore` after instantiation.\n- `sourceName` is set (`MyWebApi`) — make sure the template content actually uses that token for replacement.\n\n**Verdict:** Add at least `description` and `groupIdentity` before publishing — they're effectively required for a good NuGet experience.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6e8a5d1a-e360-46c8-8e7c-114bcfa40d61","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but recommended for validation and IDE support. The standard schema URL is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages, especially if you plan to have multiple related templates. Without it, template updates may not replace older versions cleanly.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Used for versioning when multiple templates with the same `groupIdentity` exist. \n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Optional but commonly set for project templates.\n\n5. **`defaultValue` for Framework is \"net9.0\"** — This is fine, but the `sourceName` replacement and framework choice should align with the actual project files.\n\n6. **Missing `description`** — There's no top-level `description` field. This is strongly recommended since NuGet Gallery and `dotnet new` search results display it.\n\n7. **No `postActions`** — Optional, but commonly used for restore.\n\nThe critical gaps are the `description` field for discoverability and `groupIdentity` for proper versioning in NuGet, though neither blocks an initial publish.","outputTokens":760},"id":"c0f2935b-84e1-4ab3-8289-fa6be16c1be4","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:40:11.883Z","parentId":"3d2e194f-4fdb-4b74-8c77-7099d1fc4f4f"}
